@harupy I was able to register the model once I removed the forward-slash (`/`) at the end of `source` parameter

```python
from mlflow.tracking.client import MlflowClient
client = MlflowClient()
client.create_registered_model("HPP")
result = client.create_model_version(name="HPP",
# source="s3://sagemaker-us-east-1-830861431234/mlruns/6dcb10fbc2b24f46bb4b29ed0ed54268/artifacts/model/" #Removed this last forward slash,
source="s3://sagemaker-us-east-1-830861431234/mlruns/6dcb10fbc2b24f46bb4b29ed0ed54268/artifacts/model",
run_id="6dcb10fbc2b24f46bb4b29ed0ed54268")
```
Does the UI issue still persist?

> Does the UI issues still persist?

Nope. The UI works fine now.

I'm still trying to figure out why this error occurs but the error message:

```
 TypeError: Cannot read property 'flavors' of undefined
```

https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/blob/82a11599fc9f464058e5d0bb9ecd7b12446d4646/mlflow/server/js/src/common/utils/Utils.js#L586

is causing the error.

I am also getting this exact same error and does seem to be the line that @harupy pointed out.

@sylus How did you encounter this error?

I think upgrading from MLFlow 1.9.1 to 1.13.0 and then noticed one of my experiments is no longer loading the UI, though all the rest are. Is very odd and must be something to do with my registration function but not sure why I am not getting any server errors in log just the flavors issue mentioned above.

https://github.com/StatCan/kubeflow-mlops/blob/master/containers/register-mlflow/register.py

It turns out I was wrong. This line is causing the error:

https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/blob/82a11599fc9f464058e5d0bb9ecd7b12446d4646/mlflow/server/js/src/experiment-tracking/components/ExperimentRunsTableMultiColumnView2.js#L617

Code to reproduce the error:

```python
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

import mlflow
from mlflow.tracking.client import MlflowClient


with mlflow.start_run() as run:

    model = LinearRegression()
    artifact_path = "model"
    mlflow.sklearn.log_model(model, artifact_path)

    model_uri = mlflow.get_artifact_uri(artifact_path) + "/"  # add a forward slash
    # model_uri = "foo"  # this causes the same error
    registered_model_name = "test"

    client = MlflowClient()
    client.create_registered_model(registered_model_name)
    client.create_model_version(registered_model_name, source=model_uri, run_id=run.info.run_id)
    # We currently don't perform any validation against `source` parameter.
    # This allows users to pass any value to `source`.
    # The runs table breaks when it encounters a run with an unexpected registered
    # model URI (e.g. trailing forward slash, typo, etc.).
    print(client.get_registered_model(registered_model_name))
    # make sure the `source` attribute ends with "/"

    # -> lauch the MLflow UI
```
